 Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Widworthy was born about 1215, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Widworthy, was 17 and her mother, Mrs william Widworthy, was 17. She married William le Prouz Sheriff of Devon in 1240, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died about 1290, at the age of 77."},"et":{"Abt 1215–about 1290":"umbes 1215–umbes 1290","1215–1290":"1215–1290","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1244–1316":"1244–1316","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1251–1340":"1251–1340","1200–1244":"1200–1244","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","about 1290":"umbes 1290","Abt 1215":"umbes 1215","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","125